00:08:32,320 --> 00:08:33,480
 the next five weeks on this,

198
00:08:33,480 --> 00:08:35,360
 we need to come up with some kind of definition.

199
00:08:35,360 --> 00:08:38,700
 So I have done the hard work of figuring out a definition

200
00:08:38,700 --> 00:08:39,540
 that will work for us.

201
00:08:39,540 --> 00:08:41,080
 Are you ready for it?

202
00:08:41,080 --> 00:08:42,200
 It's nothing original to me.

203
00:08:42,200 --> 00:08:45,360
 It was actually quoted by a guy named Brian Zand

204
00:08:45,360 --> 00:08:47,920
 in his book, "When Everything Catches Fire."

205
00:08:47,920 --> 00:08:49,040
 And this is what he said.

206
00:08:49,040 --> 00:08:52,880
 He said, "Deconstruction is a crisis of faith

207
00:08:52,880 --> 00:08:56,020
 "that leads to either a reevaluation of Christianity

208
00:08:56,020 --> 00:08:59,840
 "or sometimes a total abandonment of Christianity."

209
00:08:59,840 --> 00:09:01,220
 Meaning the process of deconstruction

210
00:09:01,220 --> 00:09:04,220
 doesn't begin with dismantling your belief.

211
00:09:04,220 --> 00:09:05,840
 The process of deconstruction

212
00:09:05,840 --> 00:09:08,900
 begins with doubting your belief.

213
00:09:08,900 --> 00:09:11,300
 That's the precursor.

214
00:09:11,300 --> 00:09:13,220
 That's where things have to begin.

215
00:09:13,220 --> 00:09:15,900
 And the reality is most people that say,

216
00:09:15,900 --> 00:09:17,180
 "I'm deconstructing,"

217
00:09:17,180 --> 00:09:20,820
 they're really just wrestling with doubt.

218
00:09:20,820 --> 00:09:24,340
 And so that's what I want us to talk about tonight.

219
00:09:24,340 --> 00:09:27,220
 You see, often when we hear the idea of doubt,

220
00:09:27,220 --> 00:09:28,640
 when it comes to the faith,

221
